Coding without being 'technical'

I loved this article by Ben Tossell, founder of Makerpad and Community Manager at Product Hunt, on coding without being 'technical' thoroughly describing the 'art' of managing AI coding agents. It is very much aligned with my own experience coding with Claude, and btw, I also much prefer coding in terminal.

TL;DR

Ben Tossell has spent 3 billion tokens in 4 months building real software through AI agents, without reading a single line of code. His approach: CLI over web interfaces, obsessively watching agent output, and treating every bug as a learning opportunity. Key insights:

  • agents.md is your instruction manual invest time in your setup to make every session smoother

  • CLIs over MCPs simpler, less context overhead, more portable

  • Build ahead of your capability and fail forward the gaps you hit ARE the curriculum

  • There's a new programmable layer of abstraction to master not code itself, but how to work with AI agents: prompting, context, memory, skills

The term "vibe coding" undersells it. This is a new technical class people who understand systems thinking, can orchestrate AI agents, and ship real products without writing code themselves. As Ben puts it: "No piece of software feels unattainable anymore."
